Why smartphones aren't a perfect replacement
You're right that modern smartphones can fulfill this role, but there are some nuances:
Contextual accessibility: A wearable device is always "on the body," capturing physiological signals, gestures, and surroundings—things a phone in a pocket might miss.
Privacy by design: A specialized device can be designed with a hardware restriction on recording raw data—"embeddings only."
Power efficiency: A small, single-task AI chip consumes less power than a general-purpose smartphone.

